extends ../base

block metas-vars
	- var title       = 'User Guide - The Sample Editor - '
	- var description = ', documentation, user guide, the Sample Editor'
	- var keywords    = ', documentation, user guide, the Sample Editor'

block content
	section.documentation
		h1.
			User guide<br>The Sample Editor.

		p.
			#[img(src='images/docs/giada-sample-editor.png' alt='The Sample Editor')]
		
		p.
			Giada includes a powerful editor for detailed sample manipulation. While the main window provides quick and basic interaction, the Sample Editor lets you adjust several parameters such as start and end points, pitch, and more.
		p.
			The Sample Editor also provides basic tools for cutting, trimming, or silencing your sample. These are destructive operations: if you damage the sample, you will need to reload it from disk. Don't worry — the changes affect only the copy in memory, and the original file is never modified.
		p.
			In the lower-right corner of the Sample Editor, you will find additional information about the currently loaded sample, such as the original file path, size (in audio frames), duration (in seconds), bit depth, and sample rate.

		p.
			You can zoom in and out by clicking the #[strong Zoom buttons] in the top-right corner, or by holding #[code ctrl] (#[code cmd] on macOS) and scrolling the mouse wheel.
		
		h2 Transport buttons

		p.
			#[img(src='images/docs/sample-editor-preview-buttons.png' alt='Transport buttons')]

		p.
			The transport buttons let you preview the currently loaded audio sample. If you enable the #[strong Loop] checkbox, the sample plays back in a loop. You can also press the #[code spacebar] key to start and stop playback. The playhead can be repositioned by clicking anywhere in the waveform area.

		h2 Pitch

		p.
			#[img(src='images/docs/pitch-knob.png' alt='Pitch knob')] 
		p.
			The Pitch knob stretches or compresses the sample, making it sound faster or slower. It works in the same way as a turntable pitch control slider. You can change the global resampling quality in the #[a(href='documentation-configuration') Configuration Window].
		p.
			You can stretch the sample across the whole song or the current bar by pressing the #[strong To song] and #[strong To bar] buttons. Two additional operators, #[strong &times;] and #[strong &div;], double or halve the sample's duration, while the #[strong Reset] button restores the pitch to 1.0.

		h2 Range

		p.
			#[img(src='images/docs/sample-editor-range-tool.png' alt='Range tool')] 
		p.
			The range tool is used to define the sample's playback range through the begin and end points. These points are represented in the waveform area by two vertical lines with square handles: click and drag a handle to adjust a point quickly, or use the numeric input fields to specify the exact position in samples. The #[strong Reset] button restores the default configuration.
		
		h2 Shift

		p.
			#[img(src='images/docs/sample-editor-shift-tool.png' alt='Shift tool')] 
		p.
			The shift tool lets you move the sample horizontally. This is useful when you want the sample to start at a specific position without spending too much time cutting and pasting. The shift value is specified in samples and can be either positive or negative.

		h2 Editing operations

		p.
			Select a portion of the waveform with the mouse and right-click it to open a menu with the following editing tools:
		ul
			li.
				#[strong Cut] — removes a portion of the sample and stores it in memory. It can be pasted later;
			li.
				#[strong Copy] — stores the selected range in memory for later pasting;
			li.
				#[strong Paste] — pastes the data currently stored in memory. This option is also available when you right-click the waveform without a selection, allowing you to paste at a specific frame;
			li.
				#[strong Trim] — removes everything except the selected portion;
			li.
				#[strong Silence] — mutes the selected portion by setting its amplitude to 0;
			li.
				#[strong Reverse] — reverses the data in the selected range;
			li.
				#[strong Normalize] — raises the volume of the selected range to 0.0 dB;
			li.
				#[strong Fade in/Fade out] — applies a linear fade-in or fade-out;
			li.
				#[strong Smooth edges] — gently shapes the edges of a selection;
			li.
				#[strong Set begin/end here] — sets the playback range to the selection boundaries;
			li.
				#[strong Copy to new channel] — creates a new sample channel from the current selection.
		p.
			If your sample gets messed up after a mistaken edit, you can reload it from disk by clicking the #[strong Reload] button #[img.inline(src='images/docs/reload-button.png' alt='Reload button' title='Reload button')].